review_blob: Glass bomber poured a slightly hazy dark orange (SRM 13).  Medium, short duration, off tan head, that left nice sticky lacing.  Initial nose was biscuit, butterscotch, and some faint floral hops.  Taste was pine, grapefruit and some yeasty earth.  Mouthfeel was on the watery side of average.  I could have used more carbonation.  Finish was malty with chocolates that yielded to a long lasting bitter hoppy grapefruit follow-through.

Bomber poured clear orange-amber with a small head and little lacing.  Nose was citrus (grapefruit and lemon) with a hint of vanilla and pecans.  Taste was sweet, grapefruity with a lingering lemony bitterness.  Mouthfeel was light and watery.  This beer had very low carbonation.

Pours a beautiful medium honey color, small off-white head, low CO2. The nose is huge hops and citrus. First sip - refreshing, watery and then bitterness - like fresh squeezed grapefruit.  As the beer warms scents of fresh cut grass, spring flowers, light buttery carmels, and high notes of urine come through.  7/4/7/4/16

Pint bottle purchased at Sea Mart for $2.99 pours dark brown to black with low carbonation and a medium sized quickly fleeting tan head.  Mouth was generally smooth, some alcohol and bitterness lingering on the tongue.  Initial flavors of molasses, coffee and licorice were finished with malt and chocolate.  This strong beer hid its alcohol well and would pair nicely with a pot roast, parsnips, carrots, and potatoes. A 3.1: 6/3/5/3/14

11.2 oz bottle picked up at SeaMart for $4.39.  A slightly cloudy golden orange color Tripel with lots of carbonation and a lasting frothy white foam head.  Initial aroma of yeast, wheat and soap.  The beer had a slightly bitter finish that didnt last long with hints of molasses and milk chocolate.  The mouthfeel was smooth, creamy, and foamy.  No strong alcohol taste in the 8 percenter.
